            <div class='column half'>
                <h3>Outreach</h3>
                <p>
                    After you've built your list of linkless mentions it's time to start reaching out to these websites to ask for links. One of the linkless
                    mentions we found for Nike is from an article in the Daily News about
                    <a href="http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/nike-release-back-future-shoes-2015-article-1.2068815">Back to the Future brand power lace shoes</a>.
                </p>
                <p>If you scan the page or look in the source code, you'll see that there is indeed no link to nike.com.</p>
                <p>
                    Now comes the fun, creative, and challenging part &mdash; outreach. There are many approaches to this type of outreach, and there's no one correct
                    way to do this, but the general idea is that you want to send an email to the author, editor, webmaster, or anyone else who would be able to
                    add a link to the article for you.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class='column half'>
                <h3>&nbsp;</h3>
                <img alt='' src='http://www.directagents.com/directlink/images/how-it-works4.jpg' style="max-width: 650px;">
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class='row clearfix'>
            <div class='column full'>
                <p style='max-width: none'>
                    Searching for "contact us" is usually the quickest way to find contact information, but websites can have contact information in many
                    different places, and some don't have contact information at all. If this is the case, try to think outside of the box and find the contact
                    information anyway. For example, some businesses or websites will have their contact information on their FaceBook page but not their website.
                </p>
                <p style='max-width: none'>Spend some time writing customized and thoughtful outreach letters to increase your response rate.</p>
                <p style='max-width: none'>
                    If you're going to be emailing a lot of websites, you might want to create a template to work from. Make sure you customize the template for
                    each email &mdash; this will increase your response rate because your emails won't seem automated.
                </p>
                <p style='max-width: none'>Here's an example of a template:</p>
                <p>
                    Subject: Edit Request
                    <br /><br />
                    Hello [Name],
                    <br /><br />
                    My name is [Name2], and I'm a writer for [Company]. Thanks for writing about us on [URL]!
                    <br /><br />
                    If it's not too much trouble, would you mind adding a link to our site? [Your website URL]
                    <br /><br />
                    Thanks for your time!
                    <br /><br />
                    Warmly,<br />
                    [Signature]
                </p>
                <p style='max-width: none'>If you can offer an incentive, for example, a shout out on one of your social networks, that will increase your response rate even more!</p>
                <p style='max-width: none'>Lastly, try to be as cordial as possible and maintain relationships with your new contacts &mdash; you never know when you might need their help again.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
